<DOC><DOCNO> AP890719-0098 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1238EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     07-19 0336</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0349</SECOND><HEAD>Police Disperse Students Who Gathered to Hear Opposition Legislator</HEAD><DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Riot police fired tear gas to dispersestudents who had gathered to hear an address by a mavericklegislator opposed to President Robert Mugabe's ruling party.   About 5,000 students attended the meeting Tuesday night in themain public hall on the campus of Zimbabwe University organized byEdgar Tekere's Zimbabwe Unity Movement, student leaders said.   Rioting broke out when police asked Tekere to end the meeting andstudents were filing out of the hall chanting slogans at policesurrounding the hall, they said.   Some students hurled stones at advancing lines of riot police,said a student leader who requested anonymity.   There were no immediate reports of injuries or arrests butambulance crews aided students affected by tear gas.   Students said police chased rioters and fired tear gas canistersinto campus dormitories.   Tekere and his aides left the campus before the disturbancesstarted.   A police spokesman said police began withdrawing from campus soonafter dawn Wednesday. Most students reported for classes by noonWednesday, school authorities said.   The meeting was the first public gathering addressed by Tekeresince he formed his opposition party on April 30.   In May, police cited public order regulations as the reason forbanning a public rally planned by the new party in Harare. Tekerecanceled a second meeting when his supporters found themselveslocked out of a stadium where it was to take place.   Tekere, 52, who helped found the ruling party in 1963 and becameone of Mugabe's staunchest allies, was fired from the politburo andcentral committee last October.   He was dismissed after he denounced widespread top-levelcorruption.   Forming his opposition party in April, Tekere promised to rootout corruption and vowed to prevent Mugabe from establishing aone-party state in one of Africa's few Western-style democracies.   Tekere claims the broad support of students, labor leaders andpeasants in the countryside who are disenchanted with corruption,record unemployment, shortages of basic commodities and inflation.</TEXT></DOC>